<h2 id="essential-survival">10 Survival Phrases You Must Know</h2>
  <p>If you learn nothing else before your trip to Japan, memorize these ten phrases. They cover the most common situations every traveler faces and will solve 80% of your daily communication needs. Practice saying them aloud until they feel natural — pronunciation does not need to be perfect, but familiarity prevents panic in the moment.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>#</th><th>Japanese</th><th>Reading</th><th>Meaning</th><th>When to Use</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>すみません</td><td>sumimasen</td><td>Excuse me / Sorry</td><td>Getting attention, apologizing, thanking</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>ありがとうございます</td><td>arigatou gozaimasu</td><td>Thank you (polite)</td><td>After any service, help, or gift</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td>お願いします</td><td>onegai shimasu</td><td>Please</td><td>Requesting anything, ordering food</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4</td><td>はい / いいえ</td><td>hai / iie</td><td>Yes / No</td><td>Answering any question</td></tr>
      <tr><td>5</td><td>これをください</td><td>kore wo kudasai</td><td>This one, please</td><td>Pointing at items, ordering</td></tr>
      <tr><td>6</td><td>いくらですか？</td><td>ikura desu ka?</td><td>How much?</td><td>Shopping, checking prices</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7</td><td>トイレはどこですか？</td><td>toire wa doko desu ka?</td><td>Where is the toilet?</td><td>Finding restrooms anywhere</td></tr>
      <tr><td>8</td><td>英語を話せますか？</td><td>eigo wo hanasemasu ka?</td><td>Do you speak English?</td><td>When you need English help</td></tr>
      <tr><td>9</td><td>大丈夫です</td><td>daijoubu desu</td><td>It's okay / I'm fine</td><td>Declining offers, reassuring</td></tr>
      <tr><td>10</td><td>助けてください</td><td>tasukete kudasai</td><td>Please help me</td><td>Emergencies, urgent situations</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- Phrase Usage Frequency Bar Chart -->
