  <h2 id="greetings-manners">Greetings and Manners</h2>
  <p>Japanese greetings follow strict rules based on time of day and social context. Using the correct greeting shows cultural awareness and immediately creates a positive impression. Japanese people are genuinely delighted when foreigners use proper greetings — it signals respect for their culture.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Situation</th><th>Japanese</th><th>Reading</th><th>English</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Morning (until ~10am)</td><td>おはようございます</td><td>ohayou gozaimasu</td><td>Good morning (polite)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Daytime</td><td>こんにちは</td><td>konnichiwa</td><td>Good afternoon / Hello</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Evening</td><td>こんばんは</td><td>konbanwa</td><td>Good evening</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Entering a shop</td><td>いらっしゃいませ</td><td>irasshaimase</td><td>(Staff says this — no reply needed)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Leaving</td><td>失礼します</td><td>shitsurei shimasu</td><td>Excuse me (leaving politely)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Before eating</td><td>いただきます</td><td>itadakimasu</td><td>Thank you for the food</td></tr>
      <tr><td>After eating</td><td>ごちそうさまでした</td><td>gochisousama deshita</td><td>Thank you for the meal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Apologizing</td><td>申し訳ございません</td><td>moushiwake gozaimasen</td><td>I'm very sorry (formal)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Two phrases deserve special attention: <strong>いただきます</strong> (itadakimasu) is said before every meal, hands pressed together. It expresses gratitude to everyone involved in preparing the food. <strong>ごちそうさまでした</strong> (gochisousama deshita) is said after finishing. Saying these phrases in restaurants will earn you genuine smiles from staff.</p>

  <h2 id="transportation">Transportation and Directions</h2>
  <p>Japan's transportation system is world-class but can be overwhelming for first-time visitors. Trains, subways, and buses run with legendary punctuality, and station announcements are often in both Japanese and English. These phrases help you navigate with confidence when English announcements are not available.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Japanese</th><th>Reading</th><th>English</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>＿＿駅はどこですか？</td><td>__ eki wa doko desu ka?</td><td>Where is __ station?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>切符をください</td><td>kippu wo kudasai</td><td>A ticket, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>＿＿まで行きたいです</td><td>__ made ikitai desu</td><td>I want to go to __</td></tr>
      <tr><td>次の電車は何時ですか？</td><td>tsugi no densha wa nanji desu ka?</td><td>When is the next train?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>乗り換えはありますか？</td><td>norikae wa arimasu ka?</td><td>Do I need to transfer?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>右 / 左 / まっすぐ</td><td>migi / hidari / massugu</td><td>Right / Left / Straight ahead</td></tr>
      <tr><td>タクシーを呼んでください</td><td>takushii wo yonde kudasai</td><td>Please call a taxi</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ここで降ります</td><td>koko de orimasu</td><td>I'll get off here</td></tr>
      <tr><td>空港までお願いします</td><td>kuukou made onegai shimasu</td><td>To the airport, please</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Pro tip: When asking for directions, Japanese people often physically walk you to your destination rather than explaining the route verbally. If someone starts walking, they are guiding you — follow them and thank them warmly when you arrive. This incredible helpfulness is a hallmark of Japanese hospitality.</p>

  <h2 id="hotel-accommodation">Hotel and Accommodation</h2>
  <p>Whether you are staying at a luxury hotel, a traditional ryokan (Japanese inn), or a budget hostel, these phrases cover check-in, requests, and common situations. Japanese hotel staff are extremely accommodating, and even a small effort to speak Japanese is deeply appreciated.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Japanese</th><th>Reading</th><th>English</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>予約があります</td><td>yoyaku ga arimasu</td><td>I have a reservation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>チェックインお願いします</td><td>chekkuin onegai shimasu</td><td>Check-in, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>チェックアウトは何時ですか？</td><td>chekkuauto wa nanji desu ka?</td><td>What time is checkout?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wi-Fiのパスワードは？</td><td>waifai no pasuwaado wa?</td><td>What is the Wi-Fi password?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>タオルをもう一枚ください</td><td>taoru wo mou ichimai kudasai</td><td>One more towel, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>荷物を預かってもらえますか？</td><td>nimotsu wo azukatte moraemasu ka?</td><td>Can you keep my luggage?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>朝食は何時からですか？</td><td>choushoku wa nanji kara desu ka?</td><td>What time does breakfast start?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>部屋を変えてもらえますか？</td><td>heya wo kaete moraemasu ka?</td><td>Can I change rooms?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>近くにコンビニはありますか？</td><td>chikaku ni konbini wa arimasu ka?</td><td>Is there a convenience store nearby?</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>At traditional ryokan, you may encounter unique experiences like communal baths (温泉, onsen) and futon bedding. The phrase <strong>お風呂は何時まで入れますか？</strong> (ofuro wa nanji made hairemasu ka? — Until what time can I use the bath?) is essential for onsen etiquette.</p>

  <h2 id="restaurant-food">Restaurant and Food Ordering</h2>
  <p>Eating in Japan is one of the great travel experiences. From tiny ramen shops to multi-course kaiseki dinners, these phrases help you navigate any dining situation. Many restaurants have picture menus or plastic food displays, so pointing combined with basic phrases works perfectly.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Japanese</th><th>Reading</th><th>English</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>二人です</td><td>futari desu</td><td>Two people (for seating)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>メニューをお願いします</td><td>menyuu wo onegai shimasu</td><td>Menu, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>おすすめは何ですか？</td><td>osusume wa nan desu ka?</td><td>What do you recommend?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>これは何ですか？</td><td>kore wa nan desu ka?</td><td>What is this?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>＿＿アレルギーがあります</td><td>__ arerugii ga arimasu</td><td>I have a __ allergy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>お水をください</td><td>omizu wo kudasai</td><td>Water, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>お会計お願いします</td><td>okaikei onegai shimasu</td><td>Check, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>クレジットカードは使えますか？</td><td>kurejitto kaado wa tsukaemasu ka?</td><td>Can I use a credit card?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>とても美味しかったです</td><td>totemo oishikatta desu</td><td>It was very delicious</td></tr>
      <tr><td>持ち帰りできますか？</td><td>mochikaeri dekimasu ka?</td><td>Can I take it to go?</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Important cultural note: <strong>tipping does not exist in Japan</strong>. Leaving money on the table may confuse or even offend staff. The best compliment is telling the chef 美味しかったです (oishikatta desu — it was delicious). For allergy communication, common terms include: 卵 (tamago — egg), 牛乳 (gyuunyuu — milk), 小麦 (komugi — wheat), えび (ebi — shrimp), ピーナッツ (piinattsu — peanuts).</p>

  <h2 id="shopping">Shopping and Money</h2>
  <p>Japan is a shopper's paradise, from 100-yen shops (like Daiso) to luxury department stores. Tax-free shopping is available for tourists on purchases over 5,000 yen at participating stores — look for the "Tax Free" signs and bring your passport.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Japanese</th><th>Reading</th><th>English</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>見ているだけです</td><td>mite iru dake desu</td><td>Just looking</td></tr>
      <tr><td>試着できますか？</td><td>shichaku dekimasu ka?</td><td>Can I try this on?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>もっと小さいのはありますか？</td><td>motto chiisai no wa arimasu ka?</td><td>Do you have a smaller one?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>免税できますか？</td><td>menzei dekimasu ka?</td><td>Is tax-free available?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>袋をお願いします</td><td>fukuro wo onegai shimasu</td><td>A bag, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>現金のみですか？</td><td>genkin nomi desu ka?</td><td>Cash only?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>レシートをください</td><td>reshiito wo kudasai</td><td>Receipt, please</td></tr>
      <tr><td>これをもう一つください</td><td>kore wo mou hitotsu kudasai</td><td>One more of this, please</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Japan is still a heavily cash-based society, especially at smaller shops, restaurants, and vending machines. Always carry 10,000-20,000 yen in cash. Major convenience stores (7-Eleven, Lawson, FamilyMart) have international ATMs that accept foreign cards. IC cards like Suica and Pasmo work for trains and many small purchases.</p>

  <h2 id="emergency-help">Emergency and Getting Help</h2>
  <p>Japan is one of the safest countries in the world, but emergencies can happen anywhere. These phrases could be critical in urgent situations. The emergency number in Japan is <strong>110</strong> for police and <strong>119</strong> for fire and ambulance.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Japanese</th><th>Reading</th><th>English</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>助けて！</td><td>tasukete!</td><td>Help!</td></tr>
      <tr><td>警察を呼んでください</td><td>keisatsu wo yonde kudasai</td><td>Please call the police</td></tr>
      <tr><td>救急車を呼んでください</td><td>kyuukyuusha wo yonde kudasai</td><td>Please call an ambulance</td></tr>
      <tr><td>病院に行きたいです</td><td>byouin ni ikitai desu</td><td>I want to go to a hospital</td></tr>
      <tr><td>パスポートをなくしました</td><td>pasupooto wo nakushimashita</td><td>I lost my passport</td></tr>
      <tr><td>気分が悪いです</td><td>kibun ga warui desu</td><td>I feel sick</td></tr>
      <tr><td>薬局はどこですか？</td><td>yakkyoku wa doko desu ka?</td><td>Where is the pharmacy?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>大使館に連絡してください</td><td>taishikan ni renraku shite kudasai</td><td>Please contact the embassy</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- Emergency Quick Reference Card -->
  <div style="background: #ffebee; border: 2px solid #c62828; border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; margin: 24px 0;">
    <div style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.1rem; color: #c62828; margin-bottom: 12px; text-align: center;">Emergency Quick Reference</div>
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 12px;">
      <div style="text-align: center;">
        <div style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; color: #c62828;">110</div>
        <div style="font-size: 0.85rem;">Police (警察)</div>
      </div>
      <div style="text-align: center;">
        <div style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; color: #c62828;">119</div>
        <div style="font-size: 0.85rem;">Fire & Ambulance (消防・救急)</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #555; text-align: center; margin-top: 12px;">Tourist Helpline: 050-3816-2787 (English available 24/7)</div>
  </div>

  <p>For non-emergency medical issues, Japanese pharmacies (薬局, yakkyoku) can recommend over-the-counter medications. Chain drugstores like Matsumoto Kiyoshi and Welcia have staff who may speak some English. Describing symptoms with simple phrases and gestures usually works: 頭が痛いです (atama ga itai desu — I have a headache), お腹が痛いです (onaka ga itai desu — my stomach hurts).</p>

  <h2 id="cultural-tips">Cultural Tips for Communication</h2>
  <p>Knowing phrases is only half the equation — understanding Japanese communication culture ensures your words land correctly. These cultural insights prevent common misunderstandings that phrasebooks do not cover.</p>

  <h3>The Art of Indirectness</h3>
  <p>Japanese communication tends to be indirect. When someone says ちょっと... (chotto... — "a little...") and trails off, they usually mean "no" or "that's difficult." Saying no directly is considered impolite in many situations. Similarly, 考えておきます (kangaete okimasu — "I'll think about it") often means "probably no." Understanding these indirect signals prevents confusion and shows cultural sophistication.</p>

  <h3>Body Language Matters</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bowing:</strong> A slight nod (15 degrees) works for casual greetings. A deeper bow (30 degrees) shows respect. You do not need to bow as deeply as Japanese people — any bow is appreciated from a foreigner.</li>
    <li><strong>Volume:</strong> Japanese public spaces are notably quiet. Keep your voice low on trains, in restaurants, and especially in temples and shrines.</li>
    <li><strong>Pointing:</strong> Point with your whole hand (palm up) rather than a single finger. Pointing at people is considered rude.</li>
    <li><strong>Shoes:</strong> Remove shoes when entering homes, ryokan, some restaurants, and temple interiors. Look for a shoe rack or genkan (entryway step) as signals.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Start Practicing Today</h3>
  <p>The best way to prepare for travel in Japan is to start practicing these phrases now. Use our <a href="/japanese/tools/hiragana-chart/">Hiragana Chart</a> to learn reading basics, practice with the <a href="/japanese/tools/katakana-quiz/">Katakana Quiz</a> to decode loanwords you will see everywhere, and explore the <a href="/japanese/tools/jlpt-vocabulary/">JLPT Vocabulary</a> tool for systematic word building. Read our guide on <a href="/japanese/blog/hiragana-guide/">mastering hiragana</a> for the fastest path to basic literacy, and check out <a href="/japanese/blog/japanese-particles-explained/">Japanese particles explained</a> to understand how these phrases are constructed. Even 15 minutes of daily practice for two weeks before your trip will transform your travel experience.</p>


    <p><strong>Hotel and accommodation phrases:</strong> When checking into a hotel, the front desk staff will likely speak some English at international hotels, but knowing key Japanese phrases smooths the process and works at traditional ryokan (旅館) where English may be limited. Essential phrases include: <strong>チェックインお願いします</strong> (chekkuin onegaishimasu — I'd like to check in), <strong>予約した[名前]です</strong> (yoyaku shita [name] desu — I have a reservation under [name]), <strong>Wi-Fiのパスワードは何ですか</strong> (waifai no pasuwaado wa nan desu ka — What's the Wi-Fi password?), and <strong>チェックアウトは何時ですか</strong> (chekkuauto wa nanji desu ka — What time is checkout?). At a ryokan, you might also need <strong>温泉はどこですか</strong> (onsen wa doko desu ka — Where is the hot spring?) and <strong>夕食は何時からですか</strong> (yuushoku wa nanji kara desu ka — What time does dinner start?).</p>
    <p><strong>Emergency and safety phrases:</strong> While Japan is one of the safest countries for travelers, knowing emergency vocabulary provides peace of mind. The emergency number is 110 for police and 119 for ambulance/fire. Key phrases: <strong>助けてください</strong> (tasukete kudasai — Please help me), <strong>救急車を呼んでください</strong> (kyuukyuusha wo yonde kudasai — Please call an ambulance), <strong>警察を呼んでください</strong> (keisatsu wo yonde kudasai — Please call the police), <strong>病院はどこですか</strong> (byouin wa doko desu ka — Where is the hospital?), and <strong>パスポートをなくしました</strong> (pasupooto wo nakushimashita — I lost my passport). Most police boxes (交番, koban) have officers who can help with directions and minor emergencies, and they are found near every major train station.</p>
    <p><strong>Transportation phrases beyond basics:</strong> Japan's train system is world-class but can be confusing for first-time visitors. Beyond asking for directions, these phrases help you navigate efficiently: <strong>この電車は[駅名]に止まりますか</strong> (kono densha wa [station] ni tomarimasu ka — Does this train stop at [station]?), <strong>乗り換えはどこですか</strong> (norikae wa doko desu ka — Where do I transfer?), <strong>終電は何時ですか</strong> (shuuden wa nanji desu ka — What time is the last train?), and <strong>ICカードにチャージしたいです</strong> (IC kaado ni chaaji shitai desu — I want to recharge my IC card). For taxis: <strong>[場所]までお願いします</strong> ([basho] made onegaishimasu — To [place], please) and <strong>ここで降ります</strong> (koko de orimasu — I'll get off here).</p>


    <p><strong>Cultural tips for polite interactions:</strong> Japanese service culture operates on a level of politeness that can feel unfamiliar to Western travelers. Staff will bow when greeting you, and a slight nod or bow in return is appreciated. When paying at a register, place your money or card on the small tray (お皿, osara) rather than handing it directly to the cashier. Saying <strong>ありがとうございます</strong> (arigatou gozaimasu) after receiving service — at restaurants, shops, hotels — is always well-received and shows cultural awareness. At restaurants, begin your meal with <strong>いただきます</strong> (itadakimasu — I humbly receive this food) and end with <strong>ごちそうさまでした</strong> (gochisousama deshita — Thank you for the meal). These small gestures earn genuine warmth from Japanese people and often lead to better service and more personal interactions.</p>

